'''Washizu Shrine''' (わしづじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Ōhira, {{ill|lt=Numazu|Q241037|WD=Q241037|1=Numazu}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka Prefecture|Q131320|WD=Q131320|1=Shizuoka Prefecture}}<ref>[http://shizuoka-jinjacho.or.jp/shokai/jinja.php?id=4403141 鷲頭神社] - Shizuoka Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines</ref>.

It is currently a jointly administered shrine of {{ill|lt=Warikozuka Inari Shrine|Q117463192|WD=Q117463192|1=Warikozuka Inari Shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Nagaizumi|Q1204459|WD=Q1204459|1=Nagaizumi}}.

=== Overview ===
It is enshrined on a small hill (Tenman-yama) at the tip of the southern foothills of Ōhira-yama, at the south end of the Ōhira area between the {{ill|lt=Shizuura Mountains|Q11663639|WD=Q11663639|1=Shizuura Mountains}} and the {{ill|lt=Kano River|Q6364188|WD=Q6364188|1=Kano River}}, at the eastern edge of Numazu.

Also, on the summit of {{ill|lt=Mount Washizu|Q11676307|WD=Q11676307|1=Mount Washizu}} to the southwest from there stands a small shrine as the Okumiya.

It is sometimes proposed as a candidate for Ōasa Shrine, a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, but this is not considered likely because shrine tradition states that it was founded by inviting {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Takaokami-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}, a water deity, from a shrine in Iyo in {{ill|lt=Bunmei (Japan)|Q1193544|WD=Q1193544|lt=Bunmei|1=Bunmei}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1469|Q6566|WD=Q6566|1=1469}}) for prayers regarding flood control and drought<ref name="gen">[https://genbu.net/data/izu/wasidu_title.htm 鷲頭神社] - Genshōshi</ref><ref name="engi">[http://engishiki.org/izu/bun/iz140212-05.html 鷲頭神社] - Research on Engishiki Shrines</ref>.

It is said that at first it stood beside Kannondō in Togaya at the foothills of Mt. Washizu, a little southwest of the current site, but in Bunmei 13 ({{ill|lt=1481|Q6631|WD=Q6631|1=1481}}) it was moved to the summit of Mt. Washisu<ref name="engi"/>.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 7 ({{ill|lt=1874|Q7761|WD=Q7761|1=1874}}), it was moved to the summit of Tenman-yama, its current location, and Tenjin Shrine and village shrines were merged; in Meiji 8 ({{ill|lt=1875|Q7764|WD=Q7764|1=1875}}), it was ranked as a village shrine<ref name="engi"/>.

